		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">Biological assays based in the detection of an analyte binding to a surface are widely used for drug discovery, clinical testing, monitoring for biowarfare agents and in a host of other areas. For many purposes a 'homogeneous' assay is preferred (i.e. one which does not require separation and washing steps). Many of the most sensitive homogeneous assays are based on fluorescence measurements, but often these are only useful to detect small molecules and fail for larger agents such as macromolecules, spores, viruses etc. The proposed research introduces a new concept in homogeneous fluorescence bioassay, based on the phenomenon of near-field fluorescence emission at a surface. The proposed research offers a method for highly sensitive detection of binding interactions which is suitable for detection of large molecules and biological agents.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
